Abstract
Cosmological gravitational waves are gravitational waves produced from any cosmolog-
ical effect. Among various sources, the electroweak phase transition is important. The
electroweak phase transition occurs because of the electroweak symmetry breaking. In the
electroweak breaking of symmetry, the following breaking of symmetry occurs: SU(2)
U(1)
Y
U(1)
EM
. Among the phase transitions only rst order phase transitions can create
gravitational waves but second order phase transitions cannot. We also need the phase tran-
sition to be strong so that it satises the electroweak baryogenesis. In this thesis, we have
shown that the electroweak phase transition is rst order but it is not strong. Therefore, we
will reject it. To detect gravitational waves we need to go for beyond Standard Models.
We have to nd out the temperature-dependent effective potential of a particular model
(beyond Standard Model) and check whether it satises the condition of the strong rst
order phase transition or not. If not, we will immediately reject the potential. If yes then
we go for nding the expression of h
2
GW
which will tell whether it is detectable by a
particular detector or not.

Chapter 1
Introduction
In 1916, Einstein predicted the existence of gravitational waves as a consequence of his
general theory of relativity. In 2015, gravitational waves originated from a binary black
hole merger were detected by LIGO observatory (LIGO Hanford and LIGO Livingston)
[10]. Till now together with KAGRA, aLIGO (advanced LIGO) detected many gravita-
tional waves (see Fig. 1.1). So far, Gravitational wave detectors are able to detect the fol-
Figure 1.1: Diagram showing the masses of the GW soures detected so far. (Fig taken from
[1])
lowing types Binary Neutron Star (BNS), Binary Black Hole (BBH), Neutron Star-Black
Hole Binary (NSBH). But there are many other sources from which gravitaional waves are
not discovered yet either due to low sensitivity of the detectors or due to the out of the range
of the operating frequency of the detectors. To solve these problems space-based detectors
has been proposed. eLISA is the one of popular space-based detectors proposals. This de-
tector is capable of detecting gravitational waves from cosmological phase transitions. In
this thesis, we will discuss how gravitational waves from electroweak phase transitions can
3
1. Introduction
be detected. Using this we can also test different beyond standard models. But, we cant de-
tect gravitational waves if we just stick standard model. To detect gravitational wave from
electroweak phase we need to incorporate the beyond standard model cases. The gravita-
tional waves originating from different models will be different in nature. Therefore, we
can easily verify the detection possibility beyond standard models using this technique.
Once eLISA starts collecting real observational data then only a model can be completely
veried.

in vacuum we have discussed upto gravitational waves in matter in expanding universe.At
the end of this section we have discussed different types of GWs.
In chapter 3 we have focused on the Cosmological Gravitational Wave Background.
Due to its stochastic nature it is also called Stochastic Gravitational Wave Background
(SGWB). Here we have mainly calculated the expression of GW energy density.
In chapter 4, we have discussed phase transition. This is very crucial to understand the
cosmological phase transition. In this chapter we have discussed Landau theory of phase
transition and why Landau theory is important in characterising rst and second order phase
transition.
In chapter 5, we have discussed the Higgs mechanism in standard model. We have dis-
cussed how the electromagnatism and weak interaction once united to an electromagnatism
and weak interaction. We did a general discussion of GWS theory and implemented it in
the Higgs mechanism. We have also shown the corrections in the Higgs potential. In
chapter 6 we showed how the electroweak phase transition happened in the early universe.
In chapter 7, we discussed how the gravitational wave depends on various parameters.

In this chapter, we are interested in dening gravitational waves over curved background

stick to static universe. In section 2.2 we have extended it for expanding background.

2.4 Gravitational wave background
The gravitational wave background (GWB) is a random gravitational wave signal that is
potentially detectable by gravitational wave detection experiments.
2.4.1 Types of Gravitational wave background
The stochastic background can be broadly divided into two categories depending upon the
source
1. Cosmological gravitational wave background
2. Astrophysical gravitational wave background
In this thesis, we will only discuss the cosmological gravitational wave background.
Page 22
Chapter 3
Cosmological gravitational wave
backgrounds
In this chapter we have the Cosmological gravitational wave background. The main feature
of Cosmological gravitational wave background is they are statistical in nature. Due to
which we will implement ergodic hypothesis similar to statistical mechanics. We want
to nd the energy density for the cosmological gravitational wave background. which is
required the expression of h
2
GW
. The h
2
GW
term will be used to know whether that
particular signal will be detectable by a particular detector or not. This chapter mainly
follows from [9, 20].
3.1 Some examples of CGWB source
Cosmological gravitational wave background may arise from several early universe sources.
1. Time-varying scalar (classical) elds in the early universe
2. Preheating mechanisms after ination involving energy transfer from ination par-
ticles to regular matter
3. Phase transitions in the early universe (such as the electroweak phase transition)
4. Cosmic strings
The cosmological gravitational wave background has not been detected yet. If it is detected,
then it has going to have profound effect on early-universe cosmology and high-energy
physics.
In this thesis, our main focus will be electroweak phase transition.
23
3. Cosmological gravitational wave backgrounds
3.2 Stochastic nature of cosmological backgrounds
The cosmological gravitational waves are stochastic in nature. That is why it is also known
as stochastic gravitational wave background (SGWB). Here, the amplitude of the tensor
perturbation H
ij
(x, ) in eqn. 3.5 is a random variable that can be characterised only sta-
tistically by performing ensemble averages. To perform an ensemble average, many copies
of the system are needed. But in this case this procedure is not possible, as there is only
one observable universe. Therefore, in cosmology the ergodic hypothesis is used to equate
the ensemble average with either spatial and/or temporal averages, which means that by
observing large enough regions of the Universe today, or a given region for long enough
time, one has access to many copies of the system.
For the above assumption to be valid, certain conditions must be followed.
1. The universe is almost homogeneous and isotropic, so that the initial conditions of
the GW generation process are the same (even if only statistically) at every point in
space.
2. A GW source fullls causality and operates at a time when the typical size of a region
of causal contact in the universe was smaller than the causal horizon
1
today.

from [2, 3].

4.2 Symmetry in Phase Transition
In general, phase transition is associated with the breaking of symmetry. The state having
the highest symmetry is the disordered state, and the state having the lowest symmetry is
the ordered state. The highest possible symmetry is the symmetry of the systems Hamil-
tonian. As the temperature is lowered, when there is a phase transition, the symmetry is
31

frequently broken and the resultant system will have a lower symmetry.
Example
Consider an isotropic magnet in a zero magnetic eld. The Hamiltonian contains

zation and the system has rotational symmetry. But when the temperature is reduced to less
than the transition temperature, a magnetization appears spontaneously [3]. This denes
a direction, and the rotational symmetry is broken. Other systems have other symmetries
broken (see Tab 4.1).
In general the ordered phase will have a symmetry lower (i.e. less symmetric) than the

Not all transitions involve symmetry breaking. For example, the liquid-gas transition
does not involve a change of symmetry.
The ultimate explanation for the phase transition is found using renormalization group
[4].

4.6 Order Parameter
Before discussing Landau theory of phase transition, it is necessary to discuss the order
parameter. The concept of order parameter will be used in the Landau theory of phase tran-
Page 34
4. Phase Transition
sition.
An order parameter is a measure of the degree of order across the boundaries in a phase
transition system [24]. In one phase, the order parameter is zero, and in another phase it is
non-zero. It need not be macroscopic.
The order parameter can be a vector, a tensor, a pseudo-scalar, a group element, etc. The
order parameter is not unique. Any thermodynamic variable that is zero in the unordered
phase and non-zero in the adjacent phase on the phase diagram (usually ordered phase) is a
possible choice for an order parameter.
Examples:
1. In a ferromagnetic system undergoing a phase transition, net magnetization is the
order parameter.
2. For liquid/gas transitions, the order parameter is the difference in densities.
In the case of the rst-order phase transition, the order parameter discontinuously becomes
zero during the phase transition whereas in the case of 2nd order phase transition, it con-
tinuously becomes zero during the phase transition. The order of the transition depends
Figure 4.3: Order parameter in 1st and 2nd order transitions. (Fig taken from [3])
on the way the phase boundary is crossed.
Examples: In general, the liquid-gas transition is rst-order. But it is second order
when the critical point is crossed along the co-existence curve. In general, the order
parameter is one of the thermodynamic variables: magnetization for the ferromagnet, po-
larization for the ferroelectric and density for the uid. The non-thermodyanmic variable
can also be an order parameter. For example, the ground-state wave function for superuid
4
He and the pair wave function in superconductors.

5.1 The Higgs mechanism in Standard Model
This section starts with the Glashow-Weinberg-Salam model. This model describes how

The gauge theories are renonmalizable, i.e. all of the higher-order divergences can be
removed by redening a nite number of mass terms for the gauge bosons and fermions.
If we try to add mass terms for the gauge bosons to the model, the gauge symmetry would
be broken, and the resulting theory would not be renormalizable. However, spontaneous
symmetry breaking is a method of generating masses for the vector bosons and fermions of
the Lagrangian, which does not spoil gauge invariance.
We will now discuss SSB and then apply it to the SU(2) U(1) GWS model.
Spontaneous symmetry breaking
The phenomenon where the Lagrangian and equations of motion of a system to have a sym-
metry, but the solutions of the equations of motion violate the symmetry is called Sponta-
neous Symmetry Breaking (SSB).
The Higgs mechanism is the simplest method to implement SSB. The gauge symmetry
will be broken if the vacuum expectation value (VEV) of one of these elds is nonzero. All
the gauge boson elds with non-zero VEV has non-zero charge will become massive. Since
the Lagrangian itself is gauge-invariant, the theory is still renormalizable; however, the
vacuum state (i.e. the solution of the equations of motion) explicitly breaks the symmetry
which allows the vector bosons to acquire mass.

7.1.9 Dynamics of the Phase Transition: Three cases
The relative importance of each contribution in the generation of GW depends on the char-
acteristics of the PT and its dynamics. In this regard, the velocity of the bubble wall is
important. If the wall velocity is small, the thermal bath can efciently absorb the energy
available in the PT, and the GW spectrum is suppressed. If the wall velocity is relativistic,
a large portion of the energy can go into bulk motion or even into the kinetic energy of the
wall itself, and qualitatively different scenarios can arise depending on whether the bubble
wall reaches a terminal velocity or not. In the following, we consider three different sce-
narios. At the time of analyzing the GW spectrum predicted in a particular particle physics
model, it is important to understand which of the following scenarios apply. Runaway bub-
bles are the bubble, where the wall velocity has not reached a steady state and propagates
at almost the speed of light [37].
Case 1: Runaway Bubbles in Vacuum
Some models predict PTs that occur in a vacuum-dominated era. This situation arises in
models with signicant amount of supercooling. In this case, the effects of plasma are
negligible and the bubble wall will accelerate indenitely, with v
w
rapidly approaching the
speed of light.

Summary and Future Prospects
In this thesis rst we started with gravitational waves where we started with linearised
gravity without any matter. We then discussed the linearised gravity in matter. Then we
extended the denition of gravitational waves over curved spacetime. Upto this point what-
ever denitions we discussed, we stick to static universe but we know that universe is not
static. The universe is expanding continuously. We incorporated this idea into the denition
of gravitational waves.
Between the astrophysical and the cosmological gravitational waves, we discussed the
cosmological gravitational waves. The salient feature of cosmological gravitational waves
is that they are statistical in nature. That is why they are also called Stochastic Gravita-
tional Wave Background (SGWB). We used different statistical techniques and calculated
the expression of the energy density of cosmological gravitational waves. The expression
of energy density is important to get the expression of h
2
GW
.
Cosmological phase transition is one of the sources of cosmological gravitational waves.
Among different cosmological phase transitions, we are interested in the electroweak phase
transition. To understand the phase transition, rst we need to understand the rst-order
transition. In the phase transition chapter we have the Landau theory of phase transition.
If any temperature-dependent potential is given, using this theory we can nd the order of
the phase transition. Having a barrier between the two different minima is one of the major
features of the rst-order phase transition.
Electroweak phase transition happens due to electroweak symmetry breaking and this
electroweak symmetry breaking happens through Higgs mechanism. Thats why we dis-
cussed Higgs mechanism along with the temperature-dependent effective Higgs potential.
Then we discussed the electroweak phase transition. We saw that electroweak phase
transitions are rst-order phase transitions. The behavior of the potential as a result of tem-
perature variation is discussed. We also discussed how false vacuum becomes true vacuum
through thermal tunneling. We discussed the method to calculate the Euclidean action and
